[In the past 24 hours, the USA (237 339), Brazil (47 435), India (36 638), and Turkey (32 736) have reported the highest numbers of cases. A global total of 12 534 deaths were reported in the past 24 hours (3-4 Dec 2020).

Countries reporting more than 10 000 newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours (13 countries) include the USA, Brazil, India, Turkey, Russia (27 403), Italy (24 110), Germany (23 541), UK (16 298), Ukraine (15 131), Iran (13 341), Poland (13 236), Mexico (12 127), and France (11 221). A total of 62 countries reported more than 1000 cases in the past 24 hours; 33 of the 62 countries reporting more than 1000 newly confirmed cases are from the European region, 11 are from the Americas region, 10 are from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 5 are from the South East Asia region, 2 are from the Western Pacific region, and 1 is from the African region.

Comparing the 7-day averages of daily confirmed cases from the past 7 days (606 161) and those from 8-14 days ago, case counts have increased by 4.0%, while daily reported deaths (10 760) have increased by 5.5%. The USA has increased both newly confirmed cases (11.8%) and reported deaths (35.2%), which may be the start of the expected increase associated with the Thanksgiving weekend travel and gatherings. The 7-day average daily new cases reported in the USA is 188 326 and newly reported deaths is 2075. The USA has reported more than 200 000 new cases daily over the past 3 days, and over 2500 deaths per day over the past 4 days, and today (4 Dec 2020) represented over one-third of all newly reported cases (34.1%).

Impression: The global daily reported cases continue to increase with almost 700 000 newly confirmed infections in the past 24 hours. Countries in the European and the Americas regions are still showing the largest increases in daily new case counts, followed by the Eastern Mediterranean and the South East Asia regions. The USA continues to show uncontrolled transmission -- it is now one week after Thanksgiving Day [26 Nov 2020] and the expected increase in cases due to travel and gatherings may be beginning. That said, the reported numbers will start dropping as the weekend reporting decrease sets in. - Mod.MPP]
